00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,080
$100 a day from trading! Pocket change for some, 
life-changing for others! If you stay till the  

2
00:00:07,080 --> 00:00:14,904
end, you’ll discover how to day trade using smart 
money concepts, to hit this target every day!
  

3
00:00:14,904 --> 00:00:16,680
Market structure
So when I started trading,  

4
00:00:16,680 --> 00:00:20,960
I had no clue what I was doing.
I thought fancy indicators  

5
00:00:20,960 --> 00:00:24,400
were the key to success.
I just wanted to know the  

6
00:00:24,400 --> 00:00:29,200
trend and find a simple entry point!
But I couldn't figure out which way  

7
00:00:29,200 --> 00:00:32,640
the market was going!
It was confusing because  

8
00:00:32,640 --> 00:00:38,880
different time frames showed different trends.
All changed when I ditched all indicators  

9
00:00:38,880 --> 00:00:45,440
and started reading market structure!
This the foundation of everything we do!
 
  

10
00:00:45,440 --> 00:00:52,400
A bullish market is when prices keep going 
up. You'll see higher highs and higher lows. 

11
00:00:52,400 --> 00:00:57,760
This means each time the price drops, 
it doesn't go as low as before. 

12
00:00:57,760 --> 00:01:02,000
And when it goes up, it goes 
higher than the last peak. 

13
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:07,200
When price breaks through a previous 
high, we call it a "break of structure". 

14
00:01:07,200 --> 00:01:12,000
This is a key moment. It shows 
the market is getting stronger.
  

15
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:16,520
Now, real markets aren't perfect. 
They don't move in straight lines. 

16
00:01:16,520 --> 00:01:22,800
That's why we need to focus on these swing highs 
and lows. These are the big turns in price. 

17
00:01:22,800 --> 00:01:27,640
A swing low is the lowest 
point that led to a swing high. 

18
00:01:27,640 --> 00:01:34,880
So, when you see a new high form, look back. The 
lowest point before that high, is your swing low! 

19
00:01:34,880 --> 00:01:40,760
This might sound basic, but it's super 
important and many traders get it wrong. 

20
00:01:40,760 --> 00:01:46,280
They zoom in too close and miss the bigger 
picture. They might think the market is going  

21
00:01:46,280 --> 00:01:52,400
down when it's really still going up overall.
 
Let's say you're looking at a small part of  

22
00:01:52,400 --> 00:01:59,480
the chart. You might see lower lows and lower 
highs. You might think the market is going down. 

23
00:01:59,480 --> 00:02:04,840
But if you zoom out, you might see that 
this is just a small dip in a bigger  

24
00:02:04,840 --> 00:02:11,000
upward trend. If you sell here, you will 
lose money when the price keeps going up. 

25
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:16,320
That's why it's crucial to map out 
your swing highs and lows correctly.  

26
00:02:16,320 --> 00:02:21,520
It helps you see the big picture 
and trade in the right direction.
  

27
00:02:21,520 --> 00:02:26,960
In a bearish market, it's the opposite. 
You're looking for lower highs and lower  

28
00:02:26,960 --> 00:02:32,760
lows. The highest point that led to 
a new low becomes your swing high. 

29
00:02:32,760 --> 00:02:39,160
And, everything between a swing high and 
a swing low is just "internal structure". 

30
00:02:39,160 --> 00:02:44,680
It's the small moves within the bigger trend. 
Don't get too caught up in these small moves.  

31
00:02:44,680 --> 00:02:49,880
Keep your eye on the bigger trend.
 
Here's another important point: After a  

32
00:02:49,880 --> 00:02:56,160
break of structure, always expect a pullback.
This means after the price breaks through a  

33
00:02:56,160 --> 00:03:03,440
previous high or low, it will usually come back 
a bit, before continuing in the same direction. 

34
00:03:03,440 --> 00:03:09,160
Many new traders make this mistake here.
They see the price break through a level  

35
00:03:09,160 --> 00:03:14,080
and immediately want to buy or sell.
But the smart move is to wait for the  

36
00:03:14,080 --> 00:03:21,320
pullback. This gives you a better entry point.
 
Now, let's talk about strong and weak highs and  

37
00:03:21,320 --> 00:03:26,360
lows. This concept can really boost your trading.
A low's job is to make a high. A high's job is to  

38
00:03:26,360 --> 00:03:33,400
make a low. In a bullish market, we have a 
series of strong lows. A strong low is one  

39
00:03:33,400 --> 00:03:38,840
that succeeds in making a higher high.
If a high fails to make a lower low,  

40
00:03:38,840 --> 00:03:45,360
we call it a weak high. This is important for 
setting targets. In a bullish market, we like  

41
00:03:45,360 --> 00:03:52,600
to buy at strong lows and target weak highs.
Think about it this way: In a bullish market,  

42
00:03:52,600 --> 00:03:59,360
we're trying to catch higher lows. These are 
the easy trades, the continuations. In a bearish  

43
00:03:59,360 --> 00:04:05,400
market, we're looking to catch lower highs.
This concept gives you a clean framework  

44
00:04:05,400 --> 00:04:12,520
for mapping structure and setting targets. 
 
Now let's look at trend changes, also known as  

45
00:04:12,520 --> 00:04:19,720
changes of character. A bullish market doesn't 
last forever, and neither does a bearish one. 

46
00:04:19,720 --> 00:04:26,480
In a bullish market, we're seeing higher 
highs and higher lows. But at some point,  

47
00:04:26,480 --> 00:04:33,480
price will break below a strong low and form 
a lower low. This is where the trend changes. 

48
00:04:33,480 --> 00:04:40,720
Some traders want to see both a lower low and a 
lower high before they confirm a trend change. 

49
00:04:40,720 --> 00:04:46,400
That’s because sometimes, what looks 
like a trend change can be a fake-out. 

50
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:52,480
The market might grab some liquidity 
below a low and then continue up.
  

51
00:04:52,480 --> 00:04:59,720
I like to keep it simple. As soon as I see that 
lower low form, I consider it a trend change. 

52
00:04:59,720 --> 00:05:05,240
I then look for the lower high to form 
so I can trade the new bearish trend. 

53
00:05:05,240 --> 00:05:09,680
This links back to our strong 
and weak highs and lows concept. 

54
00:05:09,680 --> 00:05:15,920
When a strong low is taken out, it means a lot 
of money stepped in to push the price down. 

55
00:05:15,920 --> 00:05:21,240
This creates a strong high. We can 
use this to build our trade ideas. 

56
00:05:21,240 --> 00:05:26,080
The same applies in reverse for a 
bearish to bullish trend change. 

57
00:05:26,080 --> 00:05:31,760
We look for that higher high, then try 
to catch the higher low that follows.
  

58
00:05:31,760 --> 00:05:34,720
These changes of character aren't perfect. 

59
00:05:34,720 --> 00:05:39,680
They will often give false signals, 
because we bet on a reversal. 

60
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:43,960
A reversal is much harder 
to spot that a continuation. 

61
00:05:43,960 --> 00:05:50,360
In a bullish trend, we look for that first 
bearish change of character, to signal the  

62
00:05:50,360 --> 00:05:56,800
start of a pullback. Then we wait for a bullish 
change of character to signal the end of the  

63
00:05:56,800 --> 00:06:03,720
pullback and the formation of a higher low.
This approach works for both continuations  

64
00:06:03,720 --> 00:06:06,080
and reversals. 
 
 
Supply/demand 

65
00:06:06,080 --> 00:06:11,840
After the market structure, the next concept 
you should master is supply and demand. 

66
00:06:11,840 --> 00:06:18,560
Supply and demand zones are key spots on 
charts where big players make their moves. 

67
00:06:18,560 --> 00:06:23,880
These zones show where there's a big 
gap between buyers and sellers. 
  

68
00:06:23,880 --> 00:06:29,320
To find them, look for quick, strong 
price moves that suddenly reverse. 

69
00:06:29,320 --> 00:06:33,200
This shows a big imbalance 
that made the price jump. 

70
00:06:33,200 --> 00:06:37,840
To mark these zones, find 
where the big move started. 
  

71
00:06:37,840 --> 00:06:44,320
There are different types of zones to watch for.
First are the base zones: These form when price  

72
00:06:44,320 --> 00:06:50,600
stays in a small range for a while, then 
breaks out. The edges of this range are where  

73
00:06:50,600 --> 00:06:58,320
orders build up. When price comes back to these 
levels after a breakout, it's likely to react.
  

74
00:06:58,320 --> 00:07:05,640
We also have pivot zones: These form at key 
turning points, like swing highs and lows. They're  

75
00:07:05,640 --> 00:07:12,680
often marked by one or two special candles.
For a demand zone, look for a strong down candle,  

76
00:07:12,680 --> 00:07:19,760
where the next candle closes above its high. 
This shows a shift from selling to buying. 

77
00:07:19,760 --> 00:07:24,360
For a supply zone, it's the 
opposite: a strong up candle,  

78
00:07:24,360 --> 00:07:30,840
where the next candle closes below its low.
 
 
Considering the price action structure,  

79
00:07:30,840 --> 00:07:35,880
there are two main types of zones:
First are continuation ones:  

80
00:07:35,880 --> 00:07:41,720
This happens when there's a trend and price 
pulls back before continuing. These are  

81
00:07:41,720 --> 00:07:48,960
called rally-base-rally zones in uptrends, 
and drop-base-drop zones in downtrends.
  

82
00:07:48,960 --> 00:07:55,440
The second type is reversal zones: This 
happens when price changes trend direction.  

83
00:07:55,440 --> 00:07:59,440
These are called drop-base-rally 
or rally-base-drop patterns.
 
  

84
00:08:00,880 --> 00:08:06,880
Supply and demand zones aren't random. They 
show where buyers and sellers are most out  

85
00:08:06,880 --> 00:08:14,360
of balance. Big price moves often mean there was 
a mismatch between buying and selling pressure. 

86
00:08:14,360 --> 00:08:18,440
The key is how long price stays 
in the zone. When there's a big  

87
00:08:18,440 --> 00:08:23,680
imbalance, price won't stay long.
It will quickly move up or down. 

88
00:08:23,680 --> 00:08:29,440
So, look for zones where price only stayed 
for a short time before making a strong move. 

89
00:08:30,800 --> 00:08:35,840
The less time spent there, the more 
out of balance supply and demand are. 

90
00:08:35,840 --> 00:08:41,160
This means a higher chance of a 
good trade when price comes back.
  

91
00:08:41,160 --> 00:08:45,640
Also focus on fresh zones 
that haven't been tested yet. 

92
00:08:45,640 --> 00:08:50,600
When price revisits a zone, it can 
use up some of the waiting orders. 

93
00:08:50,600 --> 00:08:55,840
This makes the imbalance less extreme.
So, the more times a zone is hit,  

94
00:08:55,840 --> 00:09:01,320
the weaker it gets. That's why it's important 
to know the difference between an untested  

95
00:09:01,320 --> 00:09:08,040
zone and one that's been hit a few times.
The trading chances are very different.
 
 
  

96
00:09:08,040 --> 00:09:11,960
To check if a zone will 
hold, look for these things: 

97
00:09:11,960 --> 00:09:17,480
First, clear break of structure: Price 
needs to make a strong move away from  

98
00:09:17,480 --> 00:09:24,960
the zone and break nearby swing highs or 
lows. If price just hangs around the zone,  

99
00:09:24,960 --> 00:09:29,840
it might not be strong.
 
And second, inducement:  

100
00:09:29,840 --> 00:09:35,480
This means there's liquidity in front of 
the zone that could absorb moves against it. 

101
00:09:35,480 --> 00:09:40,640
For a demand zone, you want to see 
buy orders stacked up in front. 

102
00:09:40,640 --> 00:09:44,560
This could be a swing low 
or a consolidation pattern. 

103
00:09:44,560 --> 00:09:51,200
It shows traders are waiting to buy at that price. 
If there's no liquidity and price just hits the  

104
00:09:51,200 --> 00:09:59,560
zone, big players might not get involved.
 
To judge how strong a supply or demand zone is,  

105
00:09:59,560 --> 00:10:03,800
look at these things:
First, speed of price movement:  

106
00:10:03,800 --> 00:10:10,880
How fast does price move away from the zone after 
it forms? Faster moves usually mean stronger  

107
00:10:10,880 --> 00:10:19,240
zones. Quick, big moves show a strong imbalance.
 
Second, time spent at the zone: How long does  

108
00:10:19,240 --> 00:10:25,800
price stay at the level before moving? Less 
time often means it's a key turning point. If  

109
00:10:25,800 --> 00:10:31,960
price just touches a demand zone and starts 
rising right away, it might mean big buyers  

110
00:10:31,960 --> 00:10:40,120
stepped in, and bought up all the supply.
 
Third, size of the move: How far does price go  

111
00:10:40,120 --> 00:10:47,520
after hitting the zone? Bigger moves usually 
mean stronger zones. If price barely moves,  

112
00:10:47,520 --> 00:10:52,560
it's not a good sign. But a long move in 
the opposite direction after testing a  

113
00:10:52,560 --> 00:10:59,680
zone means it's probably important.
 
Fourth, volume: Look for more volume  

114
00:10:59,680 --> 00:11:05,120
when the zone forms. This shows there's 
a lot of interest at that price, and big  

115
00:11:05,120 --> 00:11:12,440
players might be buying or selling there.
 
And fifth, break of market structure: Does the  

116
00:11:12,440 --> 00:11:19,680
zone cause a break in the market structure? Zones 
that do this are usually stronger. It takes a lot  

117
00:11:19,680 --> 00:11:26,720
of money to break market structure, so these 
zones are more likely to hold in the future.
  

118
00:11:26,720 --> 00:11:31,880
So when you're trading with supply and 
demand zones, remember these key points: 

119
00:11:31,880 --> 00:11:37,320
Look for explosive price movements.
Find zones where price only stays  

120
00:11:37,320 --> 00:11:45,280
for a short time before moving sharply.
Focus on fresh zones that haven't been tested yet. 

121
00:11:45,280 --> 00:11:51,640
Check for clear breaks of structure.
Look for inducement in front of the zone. 

122
00:11:51,640 --> 00:11:55,800
And consider how fresh the zone is.
 
Liquidity 

123
00:11:55,800 --> 00:12:02,760
Day trading is all about understanding how the 
market moves. And one key concept is liquidity,  

124
00:12:02,760 --> 00:12:07,520
the amount of orders in the market.
It's essentially how much supply and  

125
00:12:07,520 --> 00:12:14,400
demand exists at different price levels.
Liquidity is what drives market movement. 
  

126
00:12:14,400 --> 00:12:20,080
Every day, millions of traders jump 
in. Many use similar strategies. 

127
00:12:20,080 --> 00:12:27,120
Buyers, thinking the market will go up, buy at 
support. They put their stops just below it! 

128
00:12:27,120 --> 00:12:33,560
Sellers do the opposite. They sell at 
resistance and put their stops above the highs. 

129
00:12:33,560 --> 00:12:39,000
Then there are breakout traders! They 
set buy and sell orders around the range. 

130
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:44,600
All these orders create a lot of 
liquidity on both sides of a range.
  

131
00:12:44,600 --> 00:12:50,160
And why does this matter? Well, it helps 
you understand how the market moves based on  

132
00:12:50,160 --> 00:12:57,280
supply and demand. It's not as simple as just 
buying at support and selling at resistance . 

133
00:12:57,280 --> 00:13:02,920
You might see a trading range after a downtrend.
Some traders, not knowing how  

134
00:13:02,920 --> 00:13:08,720
order flow works, might sell here.
Others might try to buy. And there are still  

135
00:13:08,720 --> 00:13:15,600
stop orders and breakout trades on both sides .
This is where big players come in. Banks and  

136
00:13:15,600 --> 00:13:21,640
hedge funds trade huge orders. They 
need a lot of liquidity to do this. 
  

137
00:13:21,640 --> 00:13:26,920
Let's say a big institution wants to sell a 
lot. They need to free up orders in the market. 

138
00:13:26,920 --> 00:13:32,200
This is done by triggering stop losses. 
They might push the price up first,  

139
00:13:32,200 --> 00:13:38,120
hitting those stops, before selling big.
 
Liquidity tends to accumulate in certain  

140
00:13:38,120 --> 00:13:44,120
areas of the chart. These are often popular 
chart patterns that many retail traders use. 

141
00:13:44,120 --> 00:13:51,440
First ones are old highs/lows - significant price 
points from the past that stand out on the chart. 

142
00:13:51,440 --> 00:13:57,920
These areas are like liquidity magnets. Traders 
often put their stops just beyond these levels,  

143
00:13:57,920 --> 00:14:04,480
creating clusters of orders. Smart 
money loves to target these clusters.
  

144
00:14:04,480 --> 00:14:10,760
Major swings, double tops and bottoms, 
or any pattern with equal highs or lows,  

145
00:14:10,760 --> 00:14:14,720
are prime liquidity areas. Other common spots are  

146
00:14:14,720 --> 00:14:19,880
triangles, wedges and flags .
So when analyzing charts,  

147
00:14:19,880 --> 00:14:26,320
look for areas where significant buying or 
selling orders are likely to be executed. 

148
00:14:26,320 --> 00:14:30,480
These often coincide with key 
support and resistance levels,  

149
00:14:30,480 --> 00:14:37,480
breakouts, or areas of price congestion .
 
 
 
This is the simplest way to find the closest  

150
00:14:37,480 --> 00:14:43,360
liquidity zones. It’s all about recent 
price pivots, the ups and downs in price  

151
00:14:43,360 --> 00:14:47,800
that stand out on a chart.
A pivot low is a low point  

152
00:14:47,800 --> 00:14:53,280
with higher lows on both sides.
A pivot high is the opposite - a high  

153
00:14:53,280 --> 00:14:59,040
point with lower highs on both sides.
 
And why do these matter? Well,  

154
00:14:59,040 --> 00:15:03,200
it's all about how traders think.
If someone buys when the price is  

155
00:15:03,200 --> 00:15:08,800
going up, they often put their stop-loss 
order just below the last swing low. 

156
00:15:08,800 --> 00:15:12,280
If they're selling when the price 
is going down, they put their  

157
00:15:12,280 --> 00:15:18,320
stop just above the last swing high.
This creates two types of liquidity: 

158
00:15:18,320 --> 00:15:23,880
Sell-side liquidity, where sell 
stops pile up below swing lows. 

159
00:15:23,880 --> 00:15:28,960
And buy-side liquidity, where buy 
stops gather above swing highs. 

160
00:15:29,560 --> 00:15:35,840
Big players in the market, the smart money, 
love to hunt these areas. They place orders  

161
00:15:35,840 --> 00:15:43,120
to buy below the lows and sell above the 
highs, hoping to trigger all those stops.
  

162
00:15:43,120 --> 00:15:47,800
Now, let’s find the closest pivot 
highs and lows on this chart. 

163
00:15:47,800 --> 00:15:53,800
We see a low point with higher lows on 
each side - that's sell-side liquidity. 

164
00:15:53,800 --> 00:16:01,400
And here we spot a high with lower highs 
on each side - that's buy-side liquidity. 

165
00:16:01,400 --> 00:16:07,320
As the market moves, these points change.
When price breaks above a swing high,  

166
00:16:07,320 --> 00:16:12,400
that buy-side liquidity is gone, 
and we look for the next one. 

167
00:16:12,400 --> 00:16:19,840
Same thing when price drops below a swing low 
- we find the next sell-side liquidity spot.
  

168
00:16:19,840 --> 00:16:23,920
Sometimes, you'll see multiple 
swing points close together. 

169
00:16:23,920 --> 00:16:30,880
These create what we call "equal highs" or 
"equal lows." They're like liquidity hotspots,  

170
00:16:30,880 --> 00:16:37,360
where lots of stops cluster together.
 
Now, let's talk about some key liquidity  

171
00:16:37,360 --> 00:16:43,560
levels you should always keep an eye on:
First ones are previous week's high and low:  

172
00:16:43,560 --> 00:16:49,280
These are great for framing reversals 
or as targets for price moves.
  

173
00:16:49,280 --> 00:16:57,440
Second, previous day's high and low: These can 
also frame reversals or act as price targets.
  

174
00:16:59,160 --> 00:17:07,880
Session highs and lows: These include the high and 
low from the Asian, London, and New York session. 

175
00:17:07,880 --> 00:17:12,600
These liquidity levels, plus the swing 
pivots, give you a roadmap for the  

176
00:17:12,600 --> 00:17:18,080
market. They show you where big moves 
might start or end. They're very useful  

177
00:17:18,080 --> 00:17:25,600
for planning trades within each trading day.
 
 
Smart money depend on these liquidity levels.  

178
00:17:25,600 --> 00:17:29,520
They often set up trades around them.
For example, if price is going up and  

179
00:17:29,520 --> 00:17:35,600
nearing a buy-side liquidity level, they might 
get ready to sell. Because they expect a lot  

180
00:17:35,600 --> 00:17:41,960
of buy orders to be triggered there, which 
could push price up sharply before it falls. 

181
00:17:41,960 --> 00:17:47,240
On the flip side, if price is dropping 
towards a sell-side liquidity level,  

182
00:17:47,240 --> 00:17:53,320
they might prepare to buy. They're betting that 
all those sell orders will create a quick drop  

183
00:17:53,320 --> 00:17:56,520
before price bounces back up.
 
 
Discount and premium areas 

184
00:17:56,520 --> 00:18:03,120
When you day trade, you should always aim to 
take your trade from a discount and premium area. 

185
00:18:03,120 --> 00:18:07,160
Let's say you have a range.
Or you have a break of structure,  

186
00:18:07,160 --> 00:18:12,720
and you mark the swing low that started 
the move, and the end point of the move. 

187
00:18:12,720 --> 00:18:18,160
Mark this range from the low to the 
high using the Fibonacci tool. This  

188
00:18:18,160 --> 00:18:25,040
shows the middle of the range, at the 50% 
Fib level. We call this the equilibrium. 

189
00:18:25,040 --> 00:18:32,200
Anything above the 50% is at a premium. 
Anything below is at a discount. 
 
  

190
00:18:32,200 --> 00:18:37,400
Let's say you want to buy at the middle of 
the range. If you put your stop at the low  

191
00:18:37,400 --> 00:18:45,080
and your target at the high, your risk to reward 
is 1 to 1. But the deeper into discount you go,  

192
00:18:45,080 --> 00:18:50,680
the better your risk to reward gets.
The same goes for selling. If you sell  

193
00:18:50,680 --> 00:18:56,240
at the middle, stop at the high, and 
target the low, you have a 1 to 1 risk  

194
00:18:56,240 --> 00:19:03,680
to reward. But as you get deeper into 
premium, your risk to reward improves.
 
  

195
00:19:03,680 --> 00:19:11,480
We're looking at crude oil. First, we find a 
range. We have a swing low here, then price  

196
00:19:11,480 --> 00:19:20,160
moves up. We mark from this low to this high.
Very important, ranges expand as price moves.  

197
00:19:20,160 --> 00:19:25,840
So as price goes higher, we move our 
Fibonacci tool up too. We keep doing  

198
00:19:25,840 --> 00:19:30,640
this until we see a high form.
Now, if we're looking to buy,  

199
00:19:30,640 --> 00:19:38,200
we want to find an entry in the discount zone.
Do we have one? Yes, there's a demand zone here. 

200
00:19:38,200 --> 00:19:44,240
And as price reaches into that discount 
zone, it moves higher from there.
  

201
00:19:44,240 --> 00:19:52,320
Another range, from this high down to this low. 
So we mark this one out. From here, we want to see  

202
00:19:52,320 --> 00:19:58,800
price reach into a premium of the previous range.
We're looking for short positions, so we want  

203
00:19:58,800 --> 00:20:04,280
an entry in the premium zone.
Looking left, we have a supply zone. 

204
00:20:04,280 --> 00:20:09,240
Price reaches into here, into a 
premium, and rejects the zone.
 

205
00:20:09,240 --> 00:20:10,120
Inducement

206
00:20:10,120 --> 00:20:15,080
If you want to succeed in day trading, 
you also need to master inducement. 

207
00:20:15,080 --> 00:20:20,840
Inducement is simply a move that lures 
buyers or sellers into the market,  

208
00:20:20,840 --> 00:20:26,360
creating liquidity pools that smart 
money players use to their advantage. 
  

209
00:20:26,360 --> 00:20:32,160
Inducement can help you spot potential 
reversals and entry points for trades. 

210
00:20:32,160 --> 00:20:37,600
Basically, you need to spot when the market's 
trying to trick you. That's where inducement  

211
00:20:37,600 --> 00:20:42,800
comes in. It's a smart way to figure 
out what the market's really up to.
  

212
00:20:42,800 --> 00:20:46,760
So picture this: the price is 
going up, and it looks like it's  

213
00:20:46,760 --> 00:20:51,560
about to break through a high point.
Traders who like to buy when prices  

214
00:20:51,560 --> 00:20:56,680
break out will be itching to get in!
And anyone who's betting on the price  

215
00:20:56,680 --> 00:21:02,680
going down will have their stop losses 
ready to go if it breaks that high.
  

216
00:21:02,680 --> 00:21:08,960
This is exactly when the big players, the smart 
money, decide to sell. They're betting the price  

217
00:21:08,960 --> 00:21:15,880
will drop. This is inducement: the market shows 
you one thing, but plans to do the opposite. 

218
00:21:15,880 --> 00:21:22,640
First, the big players gather up their positions. 
That's the build-up. Then, they make it look  

219
00:21:22,640 --> 00:21:27,600
like the price is going one way.
That's the inducement. Finally,  

220
00:21:27,600 --> 00:21:32,800
they do the opposite of what everyone 
expects. That's when they cash in.
  

221
00:21:32,800 --> 00:21:37,360
So, when you're looking at a chart, 
keep an eye out for these fake-outs. 

222
00:21:37,360 --> 00:21:42,960
If the trend's been going down, watch for 
a quick jump up before it drops again. 

223
00:21:42,960 --> 00:21:46,920
That's your chance to sell.
If the trend's been going up,  

224
00:21:46,920 --> 00:21:52,080
look for a quick dip before it climbs 
again. That's when you want to buy.
  

225
00:21:52,080 --> 00:21:55,800
To find inducement, you 
need to look for liquidity. 

226
00:21:55,800 --> 00:22:01,720
We talked before about strong highs and 
lows and buy-side and sell-side liquidity. 

227
00:22:01,720 --> 00:22:08,440
For instance, when you see equal lows forming 
a double bottom, that creates a support level. 

228
00:22:08,440 --> 00:22:15,320
Traders buying at this support will place their 
stop losses below these lows, creating a pool  

229
00:22:15,320 --> 00:22:23,080
of sell-side liquidity . Smart money players can 
use this liquidity to fill their own positions.
  

230
00:22:23,080 --> 00:22:27,840
To profit from inducement, you need 
to think like the big players. They're  

231
00:22:27,840 --> 00:22:32,960
looking to execute large orders without 
moving the market against themselves. 

232
00:22:32,960 --> 00:22:38,760
So they use these liquidity pools to their 
advantage. When you see price approaching a  

233
00:22:38,760 --> 00:22:46,360
strong high or low, be prepared for a potential 
fake-out move before the real trend continues.
  

234
00:22:46,360 --> 00:22:51,960
One way to use inducement in your trading 
is to focus on "liquidity sweeps". 

235
00:22:51,960 --> 00:22:57,800
This is when price briefly moves beyond 
a key level, triggering stop losses and  

236
00:22:57,800 --> 00:23:03,400
creating liquidity, before reversing.
These sweeps often occur just before a  

237
00:23:03,400 --> 00:23:08,920
significant move in the opposite direction.
 
 
When looking for inducement setups,  

238
00:23:08,920 --> 00:23:15,760
pay attention to fair value gaps and supply and 
demand zones. These are areas on the chart where  

239
00:23:15,760 --> 00:23:22,480
price has moved quickly, leaving unfilled 
orders. Price often returns to these areas,  

240
00:23:22,480 --> 00:23:28,840
creating opportunities for trades.
 
In this example, the price has been dropping. 

241
00:23:28,840 --> 00:23:33,000
Then, it tries to go lower 
but can't quite make it. 

242
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:37,880
There's this pivot high point nearby. 
If the price breaks above that,  

243
00:23:37,880 --> 00:23:40,640
it could signal a change in direction. 

244
00:23:40,640 --> 00:23:45,120
And that's exactly what happens. 
This creates what a demand zone,  

245
00:23:45,120 --> 00:23:52,680
and a fair value gap. It's like a magnet for 
the price - it often comes back to these spots. 

246
00:23:52,680 --> 00:23:58,560
And watch what happens next. Before it takes 
off higher, price does something tricky.  

247
00:23:58,560 --> 00:24:04,360
It creates a new low point, getting more 
buyers interested. Then it quickly drops  

248
00:24:04,360 --> 00:24:11,960
below that low. This is the inducement - it's 
tricking people into thinking it's going lower.
  

249
00:24:11,960 --> 00:24:15,600
This is how inducement works 
in trending markets too. 

250
00:24:15,600 --> 00:24:21,880
When the price is in an uptrend, look for 
lows to be taken out before the next leg up. 

251
00:24:21,880 --> 00:24:27,600
In this particular case, we can spot several 
potential entry points where the price ran  

252
00:24:27,600 --> 00:24:32,640
a low before continuing higher.
The key thing to watch for is how  

253
00:24:32,640 --> 00:24:38,120
the price closes around these old lows.
If it quickly bounces back after taking  

254
00:24:38,120 --> 00:24:43,600
out a low, that's a strong sign 
that the uptrend is still intact.
  

255
00:24:43,600 --> 00:24:46,920
And you need to be patient.
If you're looking at a bullish  

256
00:24:46,920 --> 00:24:52,240
inducement setup (where you think the price 
will go up after tricking people into thinking  

257
00:24:52,240 --> 00:24:58,040
it's going down), wait for the price to 
actually start moving up before you enter. 

258
00:24:58,040 --> 00:25:04,160
You might miss the absolute bottom, but 
you'll also avoid a lot of false signals. 

259
00:25:04,160 --> 00:25:08,720
Market structure mapping will make 
the difference here. I repeat,  

260
00:25:08,720 --> 00:25:15,640
inducement works best when it's aligned with 
the overall trend or at key reversal points. 

261
00:25:15,640 --> 00:25:22,360
If the market's been trending up for days, an 
inducement to the downside at a major demand could  

262
00:25:22,360 --> 00:25:25,560
signal a significant reversal.
 
 
Volume profile 

263
00:25:25,560 --> 00:25:33,080
In my own day trading journey, I saw immediate 
improvement once I started using volume profile. 

264
00:25:33,080 --> 00:25:37,120
Volume profiles are one of the 
most powerful trading tools. 

265
00:25:37,120 --> 00:25:41,920
They show how much volume 
occurred at specific price levels. 

266
00:25:41,920 --> 00:25:47,760
This is key because it gives more useful info 
than traditional volume tools, as they only  

267
00:25:47,760 --> 00:25:52,560
show total daily volume.
To use volume profiles,  

268
00:25:52,560 --> 00:25:58,240
go to the left side of your chart platform.
Look for "forecasting and measurement tools". 

269
00:25:59,200 --> 00:26:04,200
And add the "anchored volume profile". 
Then, click on your chart where you want  

270
00:26:04,200 --> 00:26:08,480
to apply the profile. 
 
 
The bars in the profile  

271
00:26:08,480 --> 00:26:16,080
show trading volume at each price level.
Bigger bars mean more volume at that price. 

272
00:26:16,080 --> 00:26:21,920
The middle line is the point of control 
- the level with the most trading volume. 

273
00:26:21,920 --> 00:26:28,400
High trading volume matters because it shows 
where buyers and sellers had lots of interest. 

274
00:26:28,400 --> 00:26:34,640
They took big action at those levels. If price 
comes back to these levels in the future,  

275
00:26:34,640 --> 00:26:38,400
there might be interest again.
This creates potential trade  

276
00:26:38,400 --> 00:26:45,480
entry and exit opportunities.
 
But don't use volume profiles alone. Combine them  

277
00:26:45,480 --> 00:26:52,840
with the concepts we talked before, key points in 
the market structure, or supply and demand areas. 

278
00:26:52,840 --> 00:26:59,400
Start by applying the anchored volume profile at 
the beginning of a price move. The profile will  

279
00:26:59,400 --> 00:27:04,640
only calculate data after that point.
The point of control shows  

280
00:27:04,640 --> 00:27:11,840
where the most volume occurred.
This high-volume zone becomes an area of interest. 

281
00:27:11,840 --> 00:27:16,000
If price returns there, it could 
present long trade chances. 

282
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:19,800
Or it could be a good exit 
target for short trades.
  

283
00:27:19,800 --> 00:27:25,480
The real power comes from pairing 
high-volume areas with key levels. 

284
00:27:25,480 --> 00:27:31,000
Zoom out and look for important 
reversal points that create a key level. 

285
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:36,880
If these align with your high-volume 
zone, it makes that zone even stronger. 

286
00:27:36,880 --> 00:27:43,000
The higher quality the zone, the more likely 
price will react there in the future.
  

287
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:48,880
Also, look for other high-volume bars 
that line up with reversal points too. 

288
00:27:48,880 --> 00:27:56,400
These combos of volume and key levels create 
high-quality zones to watch for your trades. 

289
00:27:56,400 --> 00:28:02,640
You can also apply the volume profile tool to 
larger chart areas. This helps find the best  

290
00:28:02,640 --> 00:28:07,760
key zones across a wider range.
Look for points of control that  

291
00:28:07,760 --> 00:28:14,742
line up with multiple reversal points. 
These give you key zones to focus on.
  

292
00:28:14,742 --> 00:28:17,680
10 SMA daily chart
Now, in my first 2 years of day trading,  

293
00:28:17,680 --> 00:28:22,800
my biggest problem was trading the wrong trends.
I kept getting caught in false  

294
00:28:22,800 --> 00:28:27,480
moves and choppy markets.
One time frame would show an uptrend,  

295
00:28:27,480 --> 00:28:31,760
and another one a downtrend.
You might have this problem too! 

296
00:28:31,760 --> 00:28:35,640
Which one should you trade?
In my case, the solution was  

297
00:28:35,640 --> 00:28:43,200
extremely simple! I simply monitored the 10-period 
Simple Moving Average on the daily chart. 
  

298
00:28:43,200 --> 00:28:49,760
If you need a simple way to filter “buy” and 
“sell” trades, just use this simple method. 

299
00:28:49,760 --> 00:28:55,920
Price above the moving average on the daily 
chart? Look for buys on shorter time frames.  

300
00:28:55,920 --> 00:29:02,640
If the line slopes up, it's a bullish trend.
Price below the moving average? Look for sell  

301
00:29:02,640 --> 00:29:09,280
trades. A downward slope means a bearish trend.
Price near or crossing the moving average  

302
00:29:09,280 --> 00:29:17,360
often? Wait for a clear trend or avoid trading.
 
It's that easy. Once you spot the daily trend with  

303
00:29:17,360 --> 00:29:25,360
the 10-day SMA, use this info to trade on shorter 
time frames. Monitor the market structure, find  

304
00:29:25,360 --> 00:29:32,840
your liquidity areas, mark your supply and demand 
zone and confirm these with the volume profile. 

305
00:29:32,840 --> 00:29:39,720
This way, you dodge false signals and choppy price 
action. You only trade with the bigger trend. 

306
00:29:39,720 --> 00:29:43,560
This is how you day trade 
using smart money concepts. 

307
00:29:43,560 --> 00:29:47,280
You won't get lost in a sea of 
conflicting signals. Instead, you  

308
00:29:47,280 --> 00:29:51,120
align your trades with the main market flow. And,  

309
00:29:51,120 --> 00:29:58,040
you’re ready for more smart money secrets, 
go ahead and watch one of these videos!

